  <section class="trust-section compensation-stream" id="compensation" aria-labelledby="compensation-title"><div class="shell"><p class="trust-eyebrow">COMPENSATION DECISION PATH</p><h2 id="compensation-title">Are you getting paid what you’re worth?</h2><p class="trust-intro">A single, practical path for turning a compensation promise into questions you can verify.</p>
    <div class="progress-path" aria-label="Your local pathway progress"><span data-progress="big">Big Picture</span><span data-progress="brief">Brief Overview</span><span data-progress="deep">Deep Dive</span><span data-progress="check">Knowledge check</span><span data-progress="actions">Action checklist</span></div>

    <article class="depth-section" id="big-picture" data-depth="big"><div class="depth-heading"><p>BIG PICTURE · 30 SECONDS</p><h3>Start with the whole formula, not the headline.</h3></div><div class="big-grid"><figure class="formula-graphic" aria-label="Compensation formula illustration"><span>Base salary</span><b>+</b><span>Production payment</span><b>±</b><span>Quality adjustments</span><i>= What your agreement pays</i></figure><div><p><strong>Central insight:</strong> A compensation number is easier to evaluate when you can see the terms that determine how it is earned and reconciled.</p><ul class="fact-list"><li>Employment agreements commonly describe compensation, duties, benefits, and termination terms.</li><li>Medicare uses the Resource-Based Relative Value Scale in its physician payment methodology.</li><li>Written terms make it possible to compare offers on the same assumptions.</li></ul><p class="action-callout"><strong>Do this now:</strong> Ask for the written compensation formula and the date payments are reconciled.</p><p class="limitation">Limitations: this overview cannot determine fair pay for an individual physician or replace contract, tax, or legal advice.</p><a class="text-cta" href="#brief-overview" data-depth-link="brief">Continue to Brief Overview →</a></div></div><div class="feedback" data-feedback="big"></div></article>

    <article class="depth-section" id="brief-overview" data-depth="brief"><div class="depth-heading"><p>BRIEF OVERVIEW · 2 MINUTES</p><h3>Make every component visible.</h3></div><div class="formula-detail"><span>Base salary</span><b>+</b><span>(Production above threshold × conversion factor)</span><b>±</b><span>Quality adjustments</span><b>−/+</b><span>Reconciliation</span></div><div class="brief-grid"><div><h4>What to identify</h4><dl><dt>Base salary</dt><dd>Guaranteed compensation and its stated period.</dd><dt>Productivity threshold</dt><dd>The production level after which variable payment begins.</dd><dt>Conversion factor</dt><dd>The stated amount used to convert qualifying production into payment.</dd><dt>Attribution</dt><dd>How the agreement assigns work, collections, or other measures to you.</dd><dt>Quality adjustments</dt><dd>Any defined quality, access, or other performance component.</dd><dt>Reconciliation</dt><dd>When estimates are compared with actual results and corrected.</dd></dl></div><div><h4>Three questions to ask</h4><ol><li>What measure is used, and how is it attributed?</li><li>What is the threshold, conversion factor, and payment schedule?</li><li>When and how is the calculation reconciled?</li></ol><h4>Comparison example</h4><p>Offer A and Offer B may have the same base salary. If one begins production payment only after a higher threshold, their total payments can differ at the same volume.</p></div></div><a class="text-cta" href="#deep-dive" data-depth-link="deep">Continue to Deep Dive →</a><div class="feedback" data-feedback="brief"></div></article>

    <article class="depth-section" id="deep-dive" data-depth="deep"><div class="depth-heading"><p>DEEP DIVE · 5 MINUTES</p><h3>Build a comparison you can take into a conversation.</h3></div><div class="deep-grid"><section><h4>Worked example <small>Educational example only</small></h4><p>Assume an agreement states a $250,000 base salary, a 5,000-unit productivity threshold, and $45 per qualifying unit. At 6,000 attributed units, the variable amount is (6,000 − 5,000) × $45 = $45,000. Before any defined adjustments or reconciliation, the illustrative total is $295,000.</p><h4>Sample contract language <small>Educational example only—not contract language to rely on</small></h4><blockquote>“The agreement should state the production measure, attribution method, threshold, conversion factor, payment timing, and reconciliation process.”</blockquote><h4>Negotiation framework</h4><ol><li>Request the complete written formula and definitions.</li><li>Model a conservative and expected production scenario.</li><li>Ask what data supports the assumptions.</li><li>Have qualified counsel review the agreement.</li></ol></section><section class="calculator" aria-labelledby="calculator-title"><h4 id="calculator-title">Illustrative calculator</h4><label>Base salary <input data-calc="base" type="number" value="250000" min="0"></label><label>Attributed units <input data-calc="units" type="number" value="6000" min="0"></label><label>Threshold <input data-calc="threshold" type="number" value="5000" min="0"></label><label>Conversion factor <input data-calc="factor" type="number" value="45" min="0" step="0.01"></label><output data-calculator-result aria-live="polite">Illustrative total: $295,000</output><p>This calculator excludes adjustments, benefits, taxes, and agreement-specific definitions.</p></section></div><div class="checklist-editor"><h4>Editable action checklist</h4><label><input type="checkbox" data-action-check> I requested the written formula.</label><label><input type="checkbox" data-action-check> I identified the threshold and conversion factor.</label><label><input type="checkbox" data-action-check> I asked about attribution and reconciliation.</label><label><input type="checkbox" data-action-check> I will seek qualified advice before signing.</label></div><div class="common-mistakes"><h4>Common mistakes</h4><p>Comparing only base salary; treating an undefined measure as clear; ignoring timing and reconciliation; and relying on an educational example as legal advice.</p></div><div class="knowledge-check"><h4>Knowledge check</h4><p>Which combination makes a productivity payment easiest to evaluate?</p><button type="button" data-check="no">A headline conversion factor alone</button><button type="button" data-check="yes">Measure, attribution, threshold, factor, timing, and reconciliation</button><button type="button" data-check="no">A verbal estimate</button><p data-check-result aria-live="polite"></p></div><div class="feedback" data-feedback="deep"></div></article>

